Question: When is a medical certificate required for sick leave?
Example answer: A medical certificate is required when the absence is longer than two
  consecutive working days per period of absence; when a member of
  staff is unable to work the contractually agreed hours due to
  medical reasons; when unable to attend a disciplinary or
  underperformance hearing; when illness or accident occurs during
  annual leave; or when uncertified absences exceed ten working days
  per annum. A single medical certificate can certify an absence of up
  to a maximum of six weeks. (ECB Staff Rules, page 105)
